04582nam a22006735i 9781503600973DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202017cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036009737 a10.1515/97815036009732doi  a(DE-B1597)564569  a(OCoLC)1198929630  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0130002bisacsh1 aFreundschuh, Aaron, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Courtesan and the Gigolo :bThe Murders in the Rue Montaigne and the Dark Side of Empire in Nineteenth-Century Paris /cAaron Freundschuh. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Elite Cosmopolitanism and Gentrification in Western Paris -- tChapter Two. The Crime Scene -- tChapter Three. A Reporter's Ambition -- tChapter Four. The Courtesan's Objects -- tChapter Five. Colonial Picaresque -- tChapter Six. Criminal Detection as Colonial War by Other Means -- tChapter Seven. The Trial of a Gigolo -- tChapter Eight. The Skin Affair -- tConclusion. On Imperial Insecurity -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe intrigue began with a triple homicide in a luxury apartment building just steps from the Champs-Elyseés, in March 1887. A high-class prostitute and two others, one of them a child, had been stabbed to death-the latest in a string of unsolved murders targeting women of the Parisian demimonde. Newspapers eagerly reported the lurid details, and when the police arrested Enrico Pranzini, a charismatic and handsome Egyptian migrant, the story became an international sensation. As the case descended into scandal and papers fanned the flames of anti-immigrant politics, the investigation became thoroughly enmeshed with the crisis-driven political climate of the French Third Republic and the rise of xenophobic right-wing movements. Aaron Freundschuh's account of the "Pranzini Affair" recreates not just the intricacies of the investigation and the raucous courtroom trial, but also the jockeying for status among rival players-reporters, police detectives, doctors, and magistrates-who all stood to gain professional advantage and prestige. Freundschuh deftly weaves together the sensational details of the case with the social and political undercurrents of the time, arguing that the racially charged portrayal of Pranzini reflects a mounting anxiety about the colonial "Other" within France's own borders. Pranzini's case provides a window into a transformational decade for the history of immigration, nationalism, and empire in France.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aMurderxHistoryx19th centuryxFrancexParis. 0aMurderxInvestigationxHistoryx19th centuryxFrance. 0aMurderxInvestigationzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aMurderzFrancezParisxHistoryy19th century. 0aTrials (Murder)xHistoryx19th centuryxFrance. 0aTrials (Murder)zFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aXenophobiaxHistoryx19th centuryxFrance. 0aXenophobiazFrancexHistoryy19th century. 4aEmpire. 4aFrance. 4acosmopolitanism. 4acrime. 4aimmigration. 4ajournalism. 4amurder. 4apolice. 4asexuality. 4axenophobia. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360097340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503600973423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503600973.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles